{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_greenville_ver01/data/sn95047217/00529042292/1946040401/0075.xml":{"full_text":"Miami Awarded\n$47,000 to Aid\nCity Planning\nAllocation by the federal gov\nernment of $47,000 for the plan\nning of five big construction jobs\nin Miami provides the city with\nits best form of insurance against\npostwar depression in the opinion\nof Research Director O. P. Hart.\nHart, explaining that the city\nhas been granted that much of a\n130,000,000 federal appropriation\nfur postwar planning throughout\nthe nation, predicted that if an\nother depression should come the\nadvance planning would pay off\nin worthwhile projects instead of\na return to WPA leaf raking.\nIhe city up to now has been\ngranted $25,000 for planning a\ni dn American center on MacAr\ntnur causeway; $12,000 for a new\n..brary; $B,OOO to be spent in de\nnning a new bridge on S. Miami\nuwnue, and $2,500 to prepare for\nobstruction of four new fire sta\ntions.\nWhen the depression hit bottom\nin 1032, Hart pointed out, the gov\nernment was faced with the ne\nessity for finding some way of\nfeeding the jobless without any\nr- al idea of what to do with them.\nLeaf raking and some of the other\nlily WPA jobs resulted.\nShould the same thing occur\nup am, he predicted, the govern\nment would be able to start work\nnee on more than $1,000,000,-\nuuu m useful construction projects,\nnis time with the plans fully\ndrawn in advance.\nHart said he believed the nature\nf Miami\u2019s two largest jobs would\nare them deferad approval, pos\ns.bly in th enear future.\nWith President Truman express\n_ favor for government support\nI projects bolstering internation\ntrade and safeguarding the\n\u00fcbin health, Hart said, Miami\n>uid be well up the list with its\nFan American center and much\nceded sewage disposal project.\ni IBRARIANS' PAY HELD\nBELOW LIVING WAGE\nNEW YORK CITY\u2014Pay of\n.blic librarians is so low that\nj are able to afford only the\n...st necessities of life, it is re\ni vil in a questionnaire supplied\n191 members of the Brooklyn\njury Staff Association, as in\npreted in the spring issue of\n;ong Ourselves,\u201d the associa\nofficial publication.\nfrom our study of the ques\nuire,\u201d the report says, \u201cwe\nfeeling that at present we\nin order to buy some food\nj we can eat and be strong\nugh to work some more so we\nbuy some more and so\nthud infinitum. This is fair\ncither to ourselves nor to the\npublic.\u201d\nThe present salary scale, which\n.tarts at $ll5 a month take-home\npay and reaches a maximum of\n$205 a month, makes for an ex\ntremely low living standard for\nBrooklyn librarians, according to\nthe committee, headed by Helen\nr ogel, that conducted the sur\nvey As a result of meager\nwage.-, the report says, some li\nranan.- are compelled to limit\ntheir expenditures for food to $2O\na month, reduce medical care to a\nminimum, io all their own house\nw ik including washing and iron\nK after a full day\u2019s work.\nI'he report advocates a salary\nvf at least $235 a month for\nlibrarians, a wage necessary to\nlive decently\u201d in New York City.\nHOUSING FUND IN FIRST USE\n'UK AGO St. Louis\u2019 $300,000\no .uivng fund for emergency\nhuiu'ing a a.- put to use for the\ni rst time when the city received\nbido for three $5,000-$6,000\ntmu.es to be built for veterans.\nPuicnase.- of homes by veterans\nw il replenish the revolving fund\na.ud thus finance further construc\nt.on I'he National Association of\nHousing Officials says that gas\nand electric lines are being\nbrought to the sites by the utili\nties companies without charge as\na means of keeping purchasing\nprices at a minimum.\nLBO A L NOTICE\nIN THE IDh JUDICIAL CIRCUIT OF\nFLORIDA IN AND FOR DADI\nCOUNTS' FLORIDA IN\nCHANCERY. Ne.\nAMHxM pekalta.\nPlaintiff.\nv\u00bb\nNATALIE PERALTA.\nDefendant.\nNOTICE TO APPEAR\nTO NATAUE PERALTA\n852 Bth Avenue\nNew York New York\nT V ARE REQUIRED to file tn the\n.art and Cauee above stated on or before\nApril 11 ItHd your appearance or anewer\nthe Bill at Complaint for divorce, other\nwlae the allecationa thereof will be taken\naa confoeeed by you and decree pro con\nfeeao entered against you.\nDated thie 13th day of March.\n(Circuit Court Stall\nE B LEATHERMAN.\nClerk of the Circuit Court\nBy M C GREEN.\nDeputy Clerk\nJ/l* 21 2\u00bb. 4/4\nIN THE 11th JUDICIAL CIBCVITOF\nIWWDA IN AND FOR DADK COUN-\nTY FLORIDA. IN CHANCERY\nNe I\u00bbC3\nBOL HOCHSTESN.\nPlaintiff\nva\nI- ROTHY HVCHSTEIN.\niMfendant\nNOTICE TO APPEAR\nFu l\u00abtf\u00ab>THY H<<HSTEIN\n82 Chapel Street\nlax. k port Now York\ny< .U ARE REQUIRED to tf* th\nt urt and cause above otatod. on or bolero\nApril HH6. your appearanre to the Bill\nof Complaint for divorce, otherwise tor\nallegations thereof win be taken as con\nfeeoed by you and decree pro confesao en\ntered against you\nDated thie \u00aeth day of March. 1*46\n(Circuit Court Seal)\nE. B LEA THERMAN\nClerk of the Clreuit Court\nBy WM W STOCKING.\nDeputy Clerk\na/id-ai-M. 4/4\nInk I\nBy GEORGE LILLEY\nNEW YORK, N.Y.\u2014Top-rank.-\n*ng morning performer on the\nradio is fatherly, fiftyish Tom\nBreneman. Monday through Fri\nday (ABC), some 8,000,000 listen\ners tune in Tom's tomfooling\nwomen s quiz,\n\u201cBreakfast In\nHollywood.\u201d At\nBreneman\u2019s\nown Hollywood\nrestaurant\nbuilt as a by\nproduct of the\nshow some\n500 women reg\nularly show up\nat 8 a.m. for\nfunmaking that\nincludes, as\nstandard equip-\nTom Breneman\nnever like this\nment, a wishing\nring ceremony, hat fittings (on\nTom), an orchid to the oldest\nguest. Occasionally thrown in\nare interviews with an ostrich,\nchicken, horse or Hollywood\ncelebrity. Breneman in \u20193l quit a\nnone-too-successful acting ca\nreer to manage for 10 years West\nCoast radio stations. But manag\ning was never like this: some\n$2500 a week, a new movie, a\nSan Fernando Valley home (two\nchildren: Tom, Jr., 12; Gloria\nAnne, 17), mayor of movie\ncolony, Encino.\n22\u20148 TO CO\nJackie Kelk: \u201cHomer\u201d of CBS'\nFriday night domestic dilemma,\n\u201cThe Aldrich Family.\u201d Brooklyn\nborn Jackie has been acting since\nhe was old enough to see himself\nin a mirror. Then his father, a\nJackie Kelk\nHomer Brown\ntwo- a- day\nshaver, got\nmad, sent Jack\nie to Manhat\ntan\u2019s Profes\ni ion al Chil\ndren\u2019s School.\nKelk made his\nBroadway de\nbut at eight,\nwas the orig\ninal \u201cTerry\u201d of\n\"Terry and the\nPirates\u201d on the\nradio. At 22\n\u2018Homer Brown\u201d\nis nicely set-up. He\u2019s bought his\nown made-over farm in rustic\nPound Ridge, N.Y., where he lives\nwith his mother and sister (non\nprofessionals). He has a good en-\nFourteen Million Workers Covered\nBy Collective Bargaining Pacts,\nBureau of Labor Statistics Says\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014Organ\nized labor\u2019s fast increasing mem\nbership is emphasized by a U. S.\nBureau of Labor Statistics report\nshowing that approximately\n14,000,000 wage earners and sal\naried employes were working\nunder written union contracts in\n1945.\nThe number under such con\ntracts represent almost one-half of\nthe approximately 29,000,000\nworkers engaged in occupations in\nwhich unions are active in seeking\nwritten collective bargaining agree\nments.\nNo estimate was given of the\ntotal union membership, but it is\nobviously substantially larger than\nthe number of persons covered by\ncontracts since there are many\nunion members in unorganized\nplants and many organized fed\neral, state and city employes.\nNo estimate was given of the\ntotal union membership, but it is\nobviously substantially larger than\nthe number of persons covered by\ncontracts since there are many\nunion members in unorganized\nplants and many organized fed\neral, state and city employes.\nAbout 70 percent of the produc\ntion workers in manufacturing in\ndustries were employed under\nunion agreements in 1945 as com\npared with about one-third of the\nBANK....The A M E R I C A N W A Y\"\na YOU\u2014CONTROL THE COST!\nHERE ARE THE ADVANTAGES:\n1. JI er more win etart an areount.\nt. Na minimum balanee required.\n3. AU depooito insured u* to 35.000.\nAU traaimetlono may be handled hr\nmail.\n5. Twenty rherko for only 32.\n6. No requirrmento as to number of\nchecks to bo Mod per month.\nAMERICAN\nnational bank\n139 N. E. FIRST ST. OF MIAMI\nMEMBER FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORPORATION\nCLEAR-VIEW\n\u2022THE MOST MODERN BLIND\"\nthe ohly Complete\nWINDOW TREATMENT\n\u2014NOTHING ELSE TO BUY\u2014\nYou will wonder at the difference\nClear-View will nuke in the warm\nweather temperature of your borne, by\nway of in marvelous Sun Ray Reflec\ntion. Summer days will be cooln\u2014\nwinter days warmer indoors. and it\nwill surely protect furnishing* at open\nwindow* from driving winds and ram.\nIn addition, without baying anything\nelse you will achieve complete privacy\n\u2014on exemplary burglar protection for\nvour windows\u2014-daylight control with\nout glare\u2014ventilation and draft coo*\ncrol\u2014freedom from care ami drudgery\nof dusting and scrubbing the ordinary\ntype blinds\u2014end withal Clear-View\nprotection will triple the life of pamc\non window wood-work for your added\nsavings. Learn mote about this all-purpose window treatment from the legion of\nour satisfied customers.\nrnrr rSTIMITC- Let us send one of our Sales Engineers to explain the\nNRE I ININ IC. many-fold comforts and economies of, Clear-View\nand to give you a quantity and cost survey. No obligation of course. Simply phone\nand we will call at your convenience. Budget terms if desired.\n36 MONTHLY PAYMENTS\nORANGE BOWL SALES 4 SERVICE\n1505 W. FLAGLER ST. PHONE 3-5882\ndowment fund, hopes to retire (to\nswimming and sailing) and some\nwriting by 30. He now is writing\npart of the \"Aldrich\u201d show.\nA QUEEN A DAY\nThe radio quiz shows grow more\nfabulous. Newest in the daytime\nline is Mutual network\u2019s Monday\nthrough Friday afternoon \u201cQueen\nfor a Day.\u201d The title is not much\nof an exaggeration. The lady sel\nected from the\naudience each\nday by young\n(34), lowa born\nemcee Jack\nB a i 1 e y, ,e x\nWorld\u2019s Fair\nmidway barker,\nreceives a jack\npot of presents\n(lately: nylons,\nsilver fox furs,\ndiamonds, air\nplanes); a doll\ning up, beauty\nsalon to ward-\nJack Bailey\njackpot Jack\nrobe; the fulfilment of a pet wish.\nAmong the wishes: nap on the\nroof of the Empire State Building,\nexploring the ocean\u2019s floor in div r\ner's suit, a pre-view of one\u2019s own\nfuneral all granted. Some\nthought this would be the long\nsought quiz to end quizes. Instead,\nit brought two imitators.\nVERY LITTLE THINGS\nJo Stafford, in a year, has be\ncome a big singer (NBC \u201cSupper\nClub\u201d). In that time also she\u2019s\nbecome a littler singer (187 to\n135 pounds) Announcers in\nradio look down upon actors and\nvice versa.\nWhich puts Don\nMcLaughlin,\n\u201cMichael West\u201d\nof C B S' \"A\nWoman\u2019s Life,\u201d\nin the middle.\nOn other shows\nhe\u2019s an announ\ncer John\nLund, of the\nBob Crosby\nshow (changing\nto Friday\nnights, March\nDon McLaughlin\nit\u2019s confoosm\n8, CBS) is a\nhypnotist. A sister, Frances,\nof screen actor Van Heflin is doing\nwell in radio. She\u2019s \u201cNora\u201d of the\nnew CBS Friday night show.\n\"Holiday Co.\u201d\nworkers employed in non-manu\nfacturing industries. The Bureau\nof Labor Statistics has been pub\nlishing annual reports on the ex\ntent of collective bargaining since\n1941 and made a preliminary\nstudy in 1938. In 1941 it was\nestimated that slightly less than\none-third of the workers eligible\nfor union agreement coverage\nwere working under agreements\nas compared with about one-half\nof the workers in 1945.\nBig Gain* in Some Industrie*\nDuring the period since 1938,\nthere have been marked changee\nin a number of industries in the\nproportion of workers covered by\ncollective agreements. For exam\nple, in 1938 the aircraft industry\nwas almost entirely without union\nagreements whereas in 1945 al\nmost the entire industry was cov\nered by written agreements. The\nsame holds true of metal mining\nand the manufacturing of clocks\nand watches.\nLarge gains have also been re\ncorded in meat packing from a\nSKAGSETH\nStationery Co.. Inc.\n53 N. E. First St\u2014Ph. 2-8491\n(Across from Rod Cross)\nMIAMI CITIZEN, MIAMI, FLORIDA, APRIL 4, 1946\ncomparatively small number of\nworkers under written agreements\nin 1938 to nearly a 100 percent\ncoverage in 1945. Shipbuilding,\nwith approximately one-half of\nthe workers employed under writ\nten agreements in 1938, is now\nalso almost 100 percent covered\nby union agreements. Substantial\ngains were made also in cement,\naluminum, rubber and steel.\nOn the other hand, relatively\nlittle progress has been made in\nagriculture, beauty shops, retail\nand wholesale trade, and dairy\nproducts.\n\u201cMaintenance\u201d Clause* Jump\nAmong the various types of\nunion recognition (closed shop,\nunion shop, etc.) the most signifi\ncant change since 1941 has oc\ncurred in the number of workers\ncovered by \u201cmaintenance of mem\nbership\u201d clauses. This clause,\nworked out by the War Labor\nBoard, generally requires than an\nemploye who at the close of an\nescape period is a member of the\nunion involved must maintain his\ngood standing for the life of the\ncontract. Approximately twice as\nmany workers were covered by\nsuch clauses in 1945 as in 1941,\nthe total constituting slightly less\nthan one-third of all the workers\nunder agreement.\nApproximately two-fifths of all\nthe workers under agreement in\n1945 were covered by dues check\noff arrangements. Of these, ap\nproximately one-half were under\nthe automatic check-off and the\nothers under clauses which speci\nfied check-off and dues only by\nindividual written authorization.\nHOSPITAL LABOR PACT\nMARKS BIG ADVANCE\nSEATTLE An objective long\nsought by AFL leaders in Seattle\nhas become a reality with the sign\ning by St. Luke\u2019s Hospital of a\nmodel labor agreement between\nLocal 6, Building Service Employ\nes\u2019 Union (AFL) and hospital own\ners. This is the first top-to-bottom\nunion medical institution in the\ncity.\nThe contract covers nurses,\nward and kitchen aides and in\nsures a 4 0-hour week, time-and\na-half for the sixth day and double\ntime for the seventh day and holi\ndays.\nThe contract also provides med\nical security to employes at no cost\nto them. Wage scales, which also\napply to those engaged in the\nMedical Security Clinic, are the\nhighest in the city for medical\nworkers.\nApproximately 16,000 German\nprisoners of war are being re\nturned to Germany every month\nfrom seven southeastern states.\npeNINSUIar\nSERVICE CO.\n30 N. E. 22nd St. Phone 2-1520\n\nFraming Lumber Building Supplies\nInsulation Materials Acoustical\nPlaster\nTHE RURAL\nTELEPHONE JOB\nAHEAD\nWe ore enlarging our rural telephone ex- Ky\npension activities just as rapidly as equipment Ki\nand materials become available. H\nAt many places we have to install more WA -jzr\nequipment at the central office, in addition HL\nto building telephone lines out into the rural B 2\nareas, before we can furnish service. RI vL\nAt other places we even have to construct K\nor enlarge buildings before we have space to Hn\ninstall the central office equipment. K\nMuch depends on how rapidly manufac- D\nhirers can supply the necessary equipment\nand materials. However, we will continue to Kn\ngo forward with our rural telephone work os Kh|\nfast os conditions permit.\nSOUTHERN BELL TELEPHONE Hl 5?\nAND TELEGRAPH COMPANY H\nlacsrperated\nUnion-Management Cash Prizes Offered\nFor Best Plans to Lower Electrical\nCosts in New York Home Building\nNEW YORK ClTY\u2014Labor and\nmanagement in the New York\nelectrical construction industry\nhave announced the setting up of\na $6,000 fund for prizes for sug\ngestions from workers on the job\nto lower the cost and help speed\nhome building.\nThe winning prize will be $2,000\nin cash in addition to interim\nprizes ranging from $350 in vic\ntory bonds down to smaller cash\nawards.\nThe fund was set up by the New\u2019\nYork Electrical Contractors\u2019 Asso\nciation, Inc., and Local 3 of the\nInternational Brotherhood of Elec\ntrical workers, each organization\ncontributing $3,000.\nCreation of the prize fund fol\nlows a recent decision by Local 3\nand 364 contractors to promote\nthe use of high-speed tools, equip\nment, and methods in an effort to\nspeed housing construction. The\nunions and employers also ex\nchanged no-strike, no lock-out\npledges for the duration of the\nhousing shortage. The union also\nhas voluntarily relinquished its\ncontractual right to time-and-one\nhalf for overtime and agreed to\nwork two shifts at regular rates.\nEmployers and the union also\nannounced the formation of a co\nordinating committee for improv\ning installation practices for the\nelectrical contracting industry.\nMembers of this committee, which\nis composed of workers and em\nployers, will judge the winning\nawards.\nThe 10,000 construction mem\nbers of the electrical union have\nbeen notified by mail of the pur\npose, terms and conditions of the\ncontest. All journeymen, foremen\nand superintendents, who are\nWhite Belt\nDairy\nServing Greater Miami for Mor*\nThan a Quarter Century\nMilk and Dairy Products from\nOur Own Certified Govern\nment Tested Herd.\nMIAMI. FLA. DIAL 7-2411\nmembers of Local 3, are eligible\nto participate.\nIn discussing the formation of\nthe $6,000 prize fund, Harry Van\nArsdale, Jr., business manager of\nLocal 3, said:\n\u201cThe problem in the electrical\nconstruction industry is not wages,\nhours, or conditions, but rather to\nmake labor and management more\nproductive as part of a sound re\nconversion program.\u201d\nEfrem A. Kahn, president of\nthe New York Electrical Contrac\ntors\u2019 Association, Inc., said:\n\u201cWe are determined to make\ndrastic cuts in the cost of elec\ntrial construction in New York.\nWorkers in the industry need have\nno fear that the use of stream\nlined methods and high-speed tools\nwill reduce employment oppor\ntunities. As construction gets\nunder way there is very likely to\nbe a tight labor situation. The\nnext 10 years will be primarily a\nbuilding decade.\n\u201cIt is to be hoped that em\nployers and workers in other build\ning trades join us in this effort\nto speed construction and lower\nthe cost of dwellings for a hous\ning-hungry people.\u201d\nCUSHMAN\nV BAKING CO.\n1310 W. Flagler St.\n119 Saybold Arcade\nSand\nCushman's Famous\nTROPICAL\nFRUIT CAKE\nLb. $l.OO\nAlso Gift Boxes of Cookies\nReedy for Shipment\nd-d Cross\nKEMUdHSTOM\n51 E. Hagler Phone 3-6231\nC Wtp' i\n\u201cMiami, Fla.\u201d\n(RoBR' or name\nTr electrically engraved on your\nGifts from Florida\nPLASTIC PIANO BANt\nv tropical decal 96\nCOMBINATION iOr Ml it x\nCOMPACT to ..ias\u2019 a\npa n ted desig n-- ,id ^ue 298\nSAILFISH PIN 19\nFLAMINGO P:H W\nin PALM TREE Pil< 49\n11^^^ COMPACT- j\n0 hand pa-r.te i\nCIGARETTE A .l\npainted in flu\n2,49 j 149\nU W LUCITE PIANO Cl rUo a\nTuft packs or r-\nand flam ingot 9.49\nSMALL LUCITE b\n\u2014hand painte J 2 49\nPAPER WEIGH! .phe e>\ncolored Ma apT 25\nTIP^TOP j\nSUFU FOOD 17 N. W. Mh BL\u2014W. Flagler at 13th Av\u00bb f\nBTORKB M 5 N W. Mth SV-MU W. Mb BL\nALFAR\nMILK\nCREAM\nICE CREAM\n4M FLAMINGO DRIVE WEST FALM REACH\nThorobreds by Dayton\nDATING-A Brand New Service of\nDayton Rubber Research\nTO HELP GUIDE YOU\nTO A WISE TIRE PURCHASE\nMake a Date with Dayton at\nPAN AMERICAN TIRE CO.\n1450 N. Miami Ave. MIAMI Phone 3 1559\nFORT LAUDERDALE\u2014 KEY WEST-\n9th and Federal Hwy., Ph. 1364 1103 Division St Phone\nPage Five","height":"27516","width":"20706"}}
